00:02:27.630 --> 00:02:30.690
about Vincent van Gogh--

00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:32.010
just because.

00:02:32.010 --> 00:02:35.430
So in September 1882,
van Gogh sent a letter

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:37.760
to his younger brother Theo.

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:41.300
And he wrote, "I long so much
to make beautiful things.

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:45.030
But beautiful things require
effort and disappointment

00:02:45.030 --> 00:02:46.830
and perseverance."

00:02:46.830 --> 00:02:49.980
And van Gogh knew a thing or two
about effort and disappointment

00:02:49.980 --> 00:02:51.120
and perseverance.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:53.070
He struggled with
mental illness.

00:02:53.070 --> 00:02:56.170
And although he was obviously
a really talented artist,

00:02:56.170 --> 00:02:58.530
he was dismissed as insane.

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:00.960
His brilliant paintings
didn't make him any money,

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:03.840
and he relied on Theo, who was
four years younger than him,

00:03:03.840 --> 00:03:05.910
to support him financially
so he could afford

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:08.220
to buy paint and canvases.

00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:11.260
But he didn't give up.

00:03:11.260 --> 00:03:12.760
Case in point.

00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:14.620
So painting was
van Gogh's passion.

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:17.800
He was driven to it despite
the adversity that he faced.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:21.140
He believed there was power in
pigments and canvases and brush

00:03:21.140 --> 00:03:22.810
strokes.

00:03:22.810 --> 00:03:25.090
And he explained
to Theo, "The great

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:27.670
doesn't happen
through impulse alone

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:29.800
and is a succession
of little things

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:31.834
that are brought together."

00:03:31.834 --> 00:03:33.250
And when I was
thinking about what

00:03:33.250 --> 00:03:35.230
I wanted to say to
you all here today,

00:03:35.230 --> 00:03:38.170
that idea stuck with me-- that
greatness or change doesn't

00:03:38.170 --> 00:03:39.940
just happen because
we want them to,

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:43.090
but because we work toward
them incrementally I'm

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:46.240
reminded of that lesson
again and again as a teacher.

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:48.280
Teaching is really
humbling work when

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:51.400
we realize that as much as
we want a student to grasp

00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:55.300
a concept or master a new skill,
their brains work and develop

00:03:55.300 --> 00:03:57.220
at their own pace.

00:03:57.220 --> 00:03:59.616
Sometimes it takes one
explanation and they've got it.

00:03:59.616 --> 00:04:01.990
Sometimes we have to go over
it again and again and again

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:04.090
and model it and reteach
it and think of a new way

00:04:04.090 --> 00:04:05.631
and think of a really
clever analogy,

00:04:05.631 --> 00:04:08.330
and then maybe they'll get it.

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:10.900
There's no one right way
to get to that end point.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:13.480
And more often than not, we're
going to mess up a few times

00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:14.960
before we get there.

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:17.170
But if we can remember
van Gogh's doggedness

00:04:17.170 --> 00:04:20.870
in his own journey, I think
there are lessons for us there.

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:24.990
So he also wrote to Theo, "Even
if one loses here and there,

00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:28.220
and even if one sometimes
feels a sort of decline,

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:31.400
the point is nevertheless
to revive and have courage,

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:34.505
even though things don't turn
out as one first thought."

00:04:34.505 --> 00:04:37.840
And I feel like that perfectly
sums up our work sometimes.

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:40.450
So often, just like
van Gogh explained,

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:43.150
things don't turn out
exactly the way we planned,

00:04:43.150 --> 00:04:46.510
but we persist because we
know that all of our students

00:04:46.510 --> 00:04:50.150
deserve opportunities
to learn and grow.

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:53.060
To me, one of the most beautiful
things about being an educator

00:04:53.060 --> 00:04:57.260
is that every single day, we
are surrounded by amazing people

00:04:57.260 --> 00:04:59.060
and their amazing minds.

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:02.660
And we walk among this
constant source of inspiration

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:03.560
in our work.

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:06.050
We're surrounded by
colleagues, by peers

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:09.590
and by students who are
incredible, brilliant people.

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:13.280
And they remind us that
even though the work is hard

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:15.150
and the work sometimes
feels impossible,

00:05:15.150 --> 00:05:17.030
we have to be relentless.

00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:20.300
We have to believe that we as
individuals can make a huge

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:23.192
impact on our students
and by extension--

00:05:23.192 --> 00:05:25.400
and this was said a little
while ago and I loved it--

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:26.090
the world.

00:05:26.090 --> 00:05:29.545
We can change the world
through our actions.

00:05:29.545 --> 00:05:30.920
During my first
year of teaching,

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:32.294
there was this
10th grade student

00:05:32.294 --> 00:05:35.930
named Sheron who reminded me
of the power one individual

00:05:35.930 --> 00:05:37.910
can have.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:40.430
At that time my
school's uniform policy

00:05:40.430 --> 00:05:44.000
required that all students had
to wear black or khaki pants.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.840
Students who showed up to school
in jeans or shorts or skirts

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:51.410
had to change in order to be
allowed to come into class.

00:05:51.410 --> 00:05:54.890
So 10th grade Sheron was a
force to be reckoned with.

00:05:54.890 --> 00:05:55.790
She was super smart.

00:05:55.790 --> 00:05:57.020
She was outspoken.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:59.379
She had incredible
leadership skills.

00:05:59.379 --> 00:06:01.670
And all throughout the previous
year as a ninth grader,

00:06:01.670 --> 00:06:03.260
she'd shown up to
school every day

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:04.760
wearing black or khaki pants--

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:06.470
following the uniform policy.

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:08.870
But that September when she
turned into a 10th grader,

00:06:08.870 --> 00:06:11.600
she showed up and she was
wearing a floor length khaki

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:13.620
skirt.

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:17.070
She told her teachers that
her religion required women

00:06:17.070 --> 00:06:19.080
to wear skirts, not pants.

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:21.690
And that she was tired of
breaking with her faith

00:06:21.690 --> 00:06:24.030
to follow the school's rule.

00:06:24.030 --> 00:06:26.610
She liked the school, she said.

00:06:26.610 --> 00:06:29.250
She just didn't
want to wear pants.

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:32.340
So her teachers consulted
with school administrators

00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:34.320
and told her that,
unfortunately, she was not

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:35.980
permitted to be in pants--

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:37.860
whoops, no, she
was not permitted

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:40.680
to be in class unless
she was in uniform,

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:42.690
unless she was wearing pants.

00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:45.960
So that day, she sat
outside in the hallway

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:47.220
and did all of her work.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:49.920
She stayed the whole
day wearing her skirt,

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:53.340
doing her work out of uniform.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:55.910
The next day, she showed up
again in another floor length

00:06:55.910 --> 00:06:57.480
khaki skirt.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:06:59.010
Again, she was told to change.

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:02.410
She refused and she did
her work in the hallway.

00:07:02.410 --> 00:07:04.450
The administrators who
made the call saw this

00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:05.910
as a really simple issue--

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:08.260
uniform policy called for pants.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.060
Sheron was not
following that policy.

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:12.010
Case closed.

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:13.510
But the situation
didn't sit right

00:07:13.510 --> 00:07:15.010
with a lot of other people.

00:07:15.010 --> 00:07:17.680
Having an eager student
sitting in the hallway all day

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:19.420
just because she
was wearing a skirt,

00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:21.086
especially because
it was out of a sense

00:07:21.086 --> 00:07:24.220
of religious obligation,
felt contrary to our values

00:07:24.220 --> 00:07:25.450
as an institution.

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:28.640
It felt like it went against
the reasons we worked with kids.

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:29.890
The reasons we were educators.

00:07:29.890 --> 00:07:31.210
We wanted to value
who they were.

00:07:31.210 --> 00:07:32.960
We wanted to show them
that they mattered.

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:35.500
And instead, we had her
sitting in the hall.

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:37.480
And the students weren't
happy about it either.

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:38.327
They called us out.

00:07:38.327 --> 00:07:39.660
They told us we were hypocrites.

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:40.810
You know how they do.

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:45.040
They threatened that they would
show up in solidarity skirts.

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:46.780
They would call our bluff.

00:07:46.780 --> 00:07:49.420
You can't keep us all
out of class, they said.

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:51.040
It's not fair, they said.

00:07:51.040 --> 00:07:53.810
The rule is stupid, they said.

00:07:53.810 --> 00:07:56.620
And over lunch and after
classes, a lot of us

00:07:56.620 --> 00:07:58.690
thought that they
might be right.

00:07:58.690 --> 00:08:00.700
They might have a point.

00:08:00.700 --> 00:08:02.860
At our school, we pride
ourselves on our approach

00:08:02.860 --> 00:08:04.150
to teaching history.

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:06.790
We use an interdisciplinary
humanities model

00:08:06.790 --> 00:08:09.880
to weave stories from history
together with literacy skills,

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:13.495
and we center our curricula
on the idea of social justice.

00:08:13.495 --> 00:08:15.370
During her ninth grade
year, the year before,

00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:18.189
Sheron had studied the history
of apartheid in South Africa.

00:08:18.189 --> 00:08:20.230
And she and her classmates
had looked at the ways

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:23.470
that South Africans
had resisted apartheid.

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:25.720
She knew about
civil disobedience--

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:28.720
the idea that protesting
an unjust rule

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:31.420
by peacefully breaking it and
accepting the consequences

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:33.039
could create change.

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:35.430
And she knew about that
because teachers at our school

00:08:35.430 --> 00:08:36.429
had taught her about it.

00:08:39.950 --> 00:08:42.559
So day after day, Sheron
showed up in a skirt,

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:45.390
embodying the principles
of civil disobedience.

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:47.450
And day after day, the
school punished her for it

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:51.490
because we had tied ourselves
to a rigid rule in a handbook.

00:08:51.490 --> 00:08:54.980
Sheron and her friends began
circulating a petition calling

00:08:54.980 --> 00:08:57.500
for a religious
exemption to be written

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:58.940
into the uniform policy.

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:01.340
They gathered the signature
of almost every single person

00:09:01.340 --> 00:09:04.860
in the school-- students and
staff and administrators.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:08.220
And so one night, they packed
into a classroom-- students,

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:11.120
staff, family members,
and Sheron in her skirt--

00:09:11.120 --> 00:09:13.340
for the monthly
school board meeting,

00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:15.320
which was usually
sparsely attended and not

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.720
at all on students' radars.

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:21.890
At the meeting, Sheron presented
the petition and made her case.

00:09:21.890 --> 00:09:25.362
The board members listened and
they approved the exemption.

00:09:25.362 --> 00:09:27.320
And looking back, it
makes sense that the board

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:28.970
voted to make the change.

00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:30.860
It was undeniably
the right change

00:09:30.860 --> 00:09:32.900
to make to an unjust rule.

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:34.970
So then why had it
taken all of the adults

00:09:34.970 --> 00:09:37.670
so long to come around?

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:40.940
I think sometimes as adults,
we default to the logic

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:43.897
of our brains instead of
the logic of our hearts.

00:09:43.897 --> 00:09:45.980
And if there are any biology
teachers in the room,

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:48.290
forgive me, because
you're probably

00:09:48.290 --> 00:09:50.930
cringing at this clearly
nonscientific exploration

00:09:50.930 --> 00:09:52.580
of anatomy, but I
started out as a poet

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:54.830
and sometimes I have to do
these things, so I'm sorry.

00:09:54.830 --> 00:09:57.740
So brain logic said that
the rule was the rule,

00:09:57.740 --> 00:09:59.622
and Sheron and her
family had signed papers

00:09:59.622 --> 00:10:00.830
agreeing to follow the rules.

00:10:00.830 --> 00:10:02.288
And so she had to
follow the rules,

00:10:02.288 --> 00:10:04.600
and that was the end
of it, case closed.

00:10:04.600 --> 00:10:07.222
Brain logic said if the rule
was bent for one student,

00:10:07.222 --> 00:10:09.430
it would have to be bent
for everyone and chaos would

00:10:09.430 --> 00:10:10.910
ensue--

00:10:10.910 --> 00:10:12.960
whatever chaos looks
like when students

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:15.370
choose their own
clothing, I don't know.

00:10:15.370 --> 00:10:19.400
Brain logic said she had worn
pants the entire year previous,

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:22.220
and so she should just
keep wearing them.

00:10:22.220 --> 00:10:24.500
But heart logic was
like, hey, guys--

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:26.236
because heart logic
is more casual.

00:10:26.236 --> 00:10:27.860
Heart logic was like,
hey, guys, here's

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:29.770
a kid who really
wants to learn, who's

00:10:29.770 --> 00:10:32.990
showing up to school every day
and completing her assignments.

00:10:32.990 --> 00:10:35.587
And we're holding her out of
class because of her clothing,

00:10:35.587 --> 00:10:37.670
which she wears, by the
way, because of her faith.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.560
Heart logic said
this doesn't feel

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:42.500
right even though
technically it might be OK.

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:45.080
Heart logic said rules
aren't as important as making

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:49.370
sure this kid feels safe
and welcome here every day.

00:10:49.370 --> 00:10:52.796
Heart logic changes minds.

00:10:52.796 --> 00:10:54.170
For the past few
years, we've had

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:58.880
students who wear skirts and
hijabs to school every day.

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:00.620
And unbeknownst to
them, their ability

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:03.560
to dress in accordance to their
religious beliefs at our school

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:07.010
is due to Sheron, a
student they've never met.

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:10.280
A student who's now an adult
and, just as a side note,

00:11:10.280 --> 00:11:12.770
is now an educator.

00:11:12.770 --> 00:11:15.260
Because of Sheron's insistence
that the school walk

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:17.720
the walk of social justice,
that it live and breathe

00:11:17.720 --> 00:11:20.450
on our policies and not
just in our curricula,

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:23.300
our handbook now contains rules
that are more just and more

00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:25.450
responsive to our community.

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:27.230
Because of Sheron,
other students

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:30.470
have since organized themselves
to successfully advocate

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:33.800
for revising the uniform
policy over the last 10 years.

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:36.140
Because of Sheron, we
now have conversations

00:11:36.140 --> 00:11:38.870
as a staff about whether
the policy still serves us

00:11:38.870 --> 00:11:43.160
as a school community or whether
it reflects our values at all.

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:48.080
And all of those changes began
with one student's action.

00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:51.650
As van Gogh wrote, "The great
doesn't happen through impulse

00:11:51.650 --> 00:11:54.470
alone and is a succession
of little things

00:11:54.470 --> 00:11:56.270
that are brought together."

00:11:56.270 --> 00:12:00.740
One person can set those
little things into motion.

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:04.070
As educators, we wholly
believe in our students' power

00:12:04.070 --> 00:12:05.900
and ability.

00:12:05.900 --> 00:12:07.772
We wouldn't do this
work if we didn't.

00:12:07.772 --> 00:12:10.270
We wouldn't be here in the
summer if we didn't, right?

00:12:10.270 --> 00:12:11.350
We care about it.

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:12.350
We know that it matters.

00:12:12.350 --> 00:12:14.350
We know our students
are powerful.

00:12:14.350 --> 00:12:16.930
But often when it comes
to believing in ourselves,

00:12:16.930 --> 00:12:19.690
in our own power and
ability as educators,

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:22.900
we do not give ourselves the
same benefit of the doubt.

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:25.930
We don't have confidence in
our own ability to make change.

00:12:25.930 --> 00:12:28.270
We think, I'm just one person.

00:12:28.270 --> 00:12:30.280
There isn't enough time.

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:32.020
But imagine if we
re-conceptualized

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:33.940
what leadership looks like.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:37.210
Sometimes we have this mythical
image of the capital L, Leader,

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:38.350
in our minds.

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:40.100
They stand out in
front of everyone else.

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:41.099
They have a fancy title.

00:12:41.099 --> 00:12:44.317
They have a business card, maybe
it's got color on one side.

00:12:44.317 --> 00:12:46.150
They've been in the
game a really long time.

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:47.920
They know everything
there is to know.

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:49.900
People trust them implicitly.

00:12:49.900 --> 00:12:51.610
They usher people
and organizations

00:12:51.610 --> 00:12:54.940
through great changes
because they have vision.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:57.771
But in practice, great leaders
don't all look the same.

00:12:57.771 --> 00:12:59.020
They don't all look like that.

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:00.000
We know that.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:01.060
There is no archetype.

00:13:01.060 --> 00:13:02.860
Some great leaders are
great collaborators.

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:03.980
They're excellent listeners.

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:04.563
They delegate.

00:13:04.563 --> 00:13:05.989
They empower.

00:13:05.989 --> 00:13:08.530
One of the ideas that's always
stuck with me that I aspire to

00:13:08.530 --> 00:13:10.570
is that great leaders
make themselves obsolete.

00:13:10.570 --> 00:13:13.589
Great leaders create
other great leaders.

00:13:13.589 --> 00:13:15.130
That's one of the
reasons why I think

00:13:15.130 --> 00:13:17.255
it's so amazing that we
have principals here today,

00:13:17.255 --> 00:13:17.930
by the way.

00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:19.466
So I want us to
rethink leadership

00:13:19.466 --> 00:13:21.340
as something that can
be held collaboratively

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:22.750
by all of the
people in this room

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:24.941
or by all the people
in the school.

00:13:24.941 --> 00:13:27.190
Calling ourselves leaders
doesn't mean that we have it

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:28.160
all figured out.

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:30.970
I call myself a teacher leader,
but I'm not a perfect teacher.

00:13:30.970 --> 00:13:33.100
If you walk into my classroom
any day of the week,

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:35.350
you're going to see me
struggling with problems.

00:13:35.350 --> 00:13:37.308
You're going to see me
trying to figure out how

00:13:37.308 --> 00:13:38.590
to engage a reluctant reader.

00:13:38.590 --> 00:13:40.240
You're going to
see me figuring out

00:13:40.240 --> 00:13:41.680
how to support an
English language

00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:43.780
learner in literary
analysis, how

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:45.940
to get a kid with
oppositional defiance disorder

00:13:45.940 --> 00:13:50.380
to stay in the classroom
and learn and feel valued.

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:52.510
I make a lot of
mistakes, and I still

00:13:52.510 --> 00:13:54.340
battle self-doubt
that tells me I'm

00:13:54.340 --> 00:13:56.120
not worthy of that
title of leader,

00:13:56.120 --> 00:13:59.520
that I don't have anything
good to tell anybody else.

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:02.050
But over the years,
I've started to expand

00:14:02.050 --> 00:14:04.990
my definition of leadership
to include things

00:14:04.990 --> 00:14:07.780
like encouraging
vulnerability in others

00:14:07.780 --> 00:14:11.920
by opening my own classroom
door and welcoming feedback.

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:14.650
To me, leadership can mean
collaborating with people

00:14:14.650 --> 00:14:18.520
who make me smarter
and more courageous,

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:20.260
but who might not
have as many chances

00:14:20.260 --> 00:14:23.530
as I have to get out there
and have their voices heard.

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:25.330
Leadership means
being the one to start

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:28.630
an uncomfortable but necessary
conversation among the staff

00:14:28.630 --> 00:14:29.920
about how we can do better.

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:32.260
Leadership means
nurturing skills

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:35.080
of leadership in other people,
including our students.

00:14:35.080 --> 00:14:37.750
Leadership means
believing, like Sheron did,

00:14:37.750 --> 00:14:39.670
that even a small
action on our part

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:43.486
might be the thing that
causes a big change.

00:14:43.486 --> 00:14:44.860
Educators need to
get comfortable

00:14:44.860 --> 00:14:47.320
seeing ourselves as leaders.

00:14:47.320 --> 00:14:50.170
We can have influence far
beyond our individual classrooms

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:52.150
if we remind ourselves
that we define

00:14:52.150 --> 00:14:55.450
what leadership looks like, and
that one person's actions can

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:59.010
have wide reaching consequences.

00:14:59.010 --> 00:15:00.900
An aside-- when I
was a little kid,

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:02.792
I did a short-lived
stint as a ballerina.

00:15:02.792 --> 00:15:04.500
It only lasted a little
while, and then I

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:07.470
quit because the teacher
wouldn't let me wear pink.

00:15:07.470 --> 00:15:09.020
No, no, she said I
had to wear pink.

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:10.290
I couldn't wear purple
and blue, and I really

00:15:10.290 --> 00:15:11.270
wanted to wear purple and blue.

00:15:11.270 --> 00:15:13.478
I wanted to be me, but she
wouldn't let me so I quit.

00:15:13.478 --> 00:15:15.520
But before I quit,
there was this recital.

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:17.250
And because I was
tall, she put me

00:15:17.250 --> 00:15:18.880
in charge of leading
one of the groups.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:20.970
So what was going to happen
was that the two groups were

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:22.261
going to come out of the wings.

00:15:22.261 --> 00:15:25.740
We're going to do this sort
of elegant ballet-like gallop.

00:15:25.740 --> 00:15:27.720
And I was going to lead
one group galloping,

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:29.130
and this other girl was going
to lead this other group.

00:15:29.130 --> 00:15:29.970
We're going to gallop out.

00:15:29.970 --> 00:15:30.595
So here we are.

00:15:30.595 --> 00:15:33.090
It's the day of the recital,
and I'm wearing my pink.

00:15:33.090 --> 00:15:36.381
And I come galloping out
of the side very elegantly.

00:15:36.381 --> 00:15:38.380
I come galloping out,
leading my group of girls.

00:15:38.380 --> 00:15:40.290
And I get onstage, and I'm
supposed to lead them around

00:15:40.290 --> 00:15:40.800
in a circle.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.420
And then something else
is supposed to happen,

00:15:42.420 --> 00:15:43.544
but it just leaves my head.

00:15:43.544 --> 00:15:45.000
I go completely blank.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:46.534
And so I'm galloping
and galloping,

00:15:46.534 --> 00:15:47.700
and everyone's following me.

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:49.610
And I catch the eye--

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:50.516
but it looks good.

00:15:50.516 --> 00:15:51.390
It looks really good.

00:15:51.390 --> 00:15:55.860
I catch the eye of the girl
who was leading the other team.

00:15:55.860 --> 00:15:57.740
It's not what it's
supposed to be.

00:15:57.740 --> 00:15:59.490
And then I catch the
eye of the girl who's

00:15:59.490 --> 00:16:01.830
leading the other team,
and I'm like, all right,

00:16:01.830 --> 00:16:03.450
I'm just going to
do what she does.

00:16:03.450 --> 00:16:06.619
So she leads her circle around,
so I lead my circle around.

00:16:06.619 --> 00:16:08.160
And then she leads
her circle around,

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:09.326
and I lead my circle around.

00:16:09.326 --> 00:16:12.550
And we end up going around
and around and around

00:16:12.550 --> 00:16:16.005
until the teacher comes out
galloping, not elegantly,

00:16:16.005 --> 00:16:17.380
and she sort of
stops everything.

00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:18.380
And she's like, hold on.

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:19.940
And she apologizes
to the audience,

00:16:19.940 --> 00:16:20.950
which is like the
worst thing ever

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:23.283
if you're performing to have
someone be like, I'm sorry.

00:16:23.283 --> 00:16:26.620
And she huddles us up and
she says, what happened?

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:28.840
And I looked at her and
I was like, I forgot.

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:30.750
So I was following her.

00:16:30.750 --> 00:16:34.120
And the other girl was like,
well, I was following you.

00:16:34.120 --> 00:16:37.160
And so I say that
to say, if we aren't

00:16:37.160 --> 00:16:38.950
going to be the ones
to step up and be

00:16:38.950 --> 00:16:40.900
the leaders in our
schools, then who is?

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:41.960
We're just going
to be following.

00:16:41.960 --> 00:16:43.810
We're going in circles
around and around and around.

00:16:43.810 --> 00:16:46.090
And so at some point, we've got
to sort of step up and be like,

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:48.000
all right, I'm going to
gallop this thing off

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:52.250
in some sort of direction to at
least get us going somewhere.

00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:54.400
We all need to see
ourselves as leaders.

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:56.470
We all need to be
brave in the face

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:58.390
of seeming impossibilities.

00:16:58.390 --> 00:17:00.160
And in order to do
that, we need to work

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:03.670
within school communities that
encourage collaboration that

00:17:03.670 --> 00:17:05.859
say it's OK to take
risks, that we're going

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:07.839
to learn from our mistakes.

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:11.420
We need to have the freedom
and the support to innovate.

00:17:11.420 --> 00:17:14.530
We need to listen to brain
logic and heart logic.

00:17:14.530 --> 00:17:17.900
And when all teachers are able
to see ourselves as leaders,

00:17:17.900 --> 00:17:20.530
as members of a powerful
collective of people who

00:17:20.530 --> 00:17:22.510
care about doing
the best work we can

00:17:22.510 --> 00:17:24.490
on behalf of our
students, we take

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:27.040
risks that have big payoffs.

00:17:27.040 --> 00:17:28.870
We try new techniques.

00:17:28.870 --> 00:17:31.840
We partner with people
we otherwise wouldn't.

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:33.970
We feel a sense of
personal responsibility

00:17:33.970 --> 00:17:35.890
for what happens in our schools.

00:17:35.890 --> 00:17:38.440
And we are relentless in
advocating for the changes

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:39.850
our students need.

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:42.160
We don't allow
fumbles or missteps

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:44.320
to deter us from
our ultimate mission

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:48.010
of getting every student
in our schools to succeed.

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:49.510
We shift the cultures
of our schools

00:17:49.510 --> 00:17:52.570
away from closed doors
and hidden struggles

00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:55.570
towards collaboration
and honesty.

00:17:55.570 --> 00:17:59.580
We remember that
change takes time.

00:17:59.580 --> 00:18:05.010
In October 1883, van Gogh wrote
his brother Theo a long letter.

00:18:05.010 --> 00:18:08.040
The letter implies that Theo was
having doubts about his career.

00:18:08.040 --> 00:18:10.500
Theo was an art dealer, but
he was getting frustrated.

00:18:10.500 --> 00:18:12.360
And he wondered if
maybe he should just

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:14.030
go into the business
of art itself--

00:18:14.030 --> 00:18:15.870
if he should try his
hand at being an artist

00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:18.120
like his brother, but he
had doubts about whether he

00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:19.506
was cut out for it.

00:18:19.506 --> 00:18:20.880
So van Gogh gave
him what I think

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:24.720
is some of the most beautiful
advice ever written.

00:18:24.720 --> 00:18:27.360
He says, "If you hear a
voice within you saying,

00:18:27.360 --> 00:18:32.280
you are not a painter, then
by all means paint, boy,

00:18:32.280 --> 00:18:36.900
and that voice will be
silenced, but only by working."

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:40.170
This year, you have the
opportunity to be painters.

00:18:40.170 --> 00:18:43.290
You have the opportunity to
be leaders within your schools

00:18:43.290 --> 00:18:48.310
and effect changes that reach
beyond just one classroom.

00:18:48.310 --> 00:18:50.940
So what kind of schools
can you envision?

00:18:50.940 --> 00:18:54.480
What kind of masterpieces
might you create?

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:58.040
There are incredible things
happening in our schools,

00:18:58.040 --> 00:19:00.930
and there is so much
more on the horizon.

00:19:00.930 --> 00:19:04.800
Our students, our Sherons,
and all the other ones--

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:05.910
they're brave.

00:19:05.910 --> 00:19:08.160
And when they discover
their leadership potential,

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:10.590
they can change the world.

00:19:10.590 --> 00:19:13.680
We need to learn that
bravery from them.

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:17.280
Inspired by our students
and for our students,

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:19.150
we have to be leaders.

00:19:19.150 --> 00:19:23.008
And by all means,
we have to paint.

00:19:23.008 --> 00:19:23.996
Thank you.

00:19:23.996 --> 00:19:27.454
[APPLAUSE]

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:37.039
So I'm a teacher, and I'm going
to ask you to do some writing

00:19:37.039 --> 00:19:38.080
and thinking and talking.

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:40.746
And then you're going to talk to
me, and it's going to be great.

00:19:40.746 --> 00:19:42.910
So I'm going to
ask you on your own

00:19:42.910 --> 00:19:45.542
to write or think about
these two questions--

00:19:45.542 --> 00:19:48.000
what beautiful things do you
want to create at your school?

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:52.561
So van Gogh said he longed so
much to make beautiful things,

00:19:52.561 --> 00:19:54.310
but he knew that
beautiful things required

00:19:54.310 --> 00:19:55.760
effort and determination.

00:19:55.760 --> 00:19:58.930
So what beautiful things do you
want to create at your school,

00:19:58.930 --> 00:20:01.330
and what stands in your way?

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:03.130
And you already did
the [INAUDIBLE]..

00:20:03.130 --> 00:20:06.030
So try to spend more time on
